      "title": "Module 1: Why memory lies about smoking",
      "text": "Human memory isn't a recording; it's a reconstruction, and it's biased toward the pleasant. Your mind tends to file the relief of smoking and quietly drop the rest — the cost, the coughing, the slavery, the times you smoked alone and joyless in the cold. So when a memory of smoking surfaces, it can come pre-edited into a flattering little scene, and that edited scene is exactly what the \"just one\" thought tries to use: \"remember how nice that was?\"\n\nThe move here is to re-edit the memory accurately — what therapists call imagery rescripting. You don't suppress the memory; you complete it. You add back everything the rosy version left out, until the snapshot tells the whole truth instead of the advertising version. A memory you've corrected can no longer be used against you."
